liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Earlier we reported that King Abdullah II of Jordan was travelling to Cairo to meet with Egyptian President Abdel-Fattah el-Sissi. The two have now had a closed-door discussion about the Israel-Gaza war and the deteriorating humanitarian situation in Gaza. In a statement, Egypt’s presidential office said the two leaders condemned Israel’s policy of “collective punishment” against Palestinians in Gaza and its efforts to displace “Palestinians from their lands to Egypt or Jordan.” Few further details were given. The two countries, which flank Israel on opposite sides, are close allies. AP
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Jordan, Egypt condemn 'collective punishment' of Palestinians

children.content: Earlier we reported that King Abdullah II of Jordan was travelling to Cairo to meet with Egyptian President Abdel-Fattah el-Sissi.
The two have now had a closed-door discussion about the Israel-Gaza war and the deteriorating humanitarian situation in Gaza.

In a statement, Egypt’s presidential office said the two leaders condemned Israel’s policy of “collective punishment” against Palestinians in Gaza and its efforts to displace “Palestinians from their lands to Egypt or Jordan.”
The two countries, which flank Israel on opposite sides, are close allies.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Professor of International Politics Scott Lucas has told the ABC there are signs in Israel's war cabinet of recognition that the past 16 years of blockade is not a sustainable solution for Israeli-Palestinian relations. "This conflict does not end, it might be eased for a bit, but it does not end until you remove the leaderships responsible for this conflict," told the ABC "That means Hamas has got to go in Gaza. It means Prime Minister [Benjamin] Netanyahu has got to go in Israel. And although Israel is still carrying out the attacks, civilians are still being killed, Hamas leaders are being killed, there are signs that within the war cabinet… they are trying to contain Netanyahu." liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: At least 3,785 Palestinians have been killed and 12,493 wounded in Israeli strikes on Gaza since October 7, the health ministry in Gaza said on Thursday. Of the total death toll, 1,524 were children and 1,000 were women, ministry spokesman Ashraf Al-Qudra told a press conference. Mr Al-Qudra added that 44 health workers had been killed in Gaza while four hospitals were out of service and 14 basic healthcare services had stopped functioning. "There are no medicine stocks in any of the hospitals in Gaza," Mr Al-Qudra added, calling on the international community to expedite the delivery of aid to Gaza. Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu told US President Joe Biden on Wednesday more than 1,400 Israelis were killed in the October 7 terrorist attacks by Hamas.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Gaza health ministry says 3,785 Palestinians killed in Israeli strikes

children.content: At least 3,785 Palestinians have been killed and 12,493 wounded in Israeli strikes on Gaza since October 7, the health ministry in Gaza said on Thursday.
Of the total death toll, 1,524 were children and 1,000 were women, ministry spokesman Ashraf Al-Qudra told a press conference.
Mr Al-Qudra added that 44 health workers had been killed in Gaza while four hospitals were out of service and 14 basic healthcare services had stopped functioning.
"There are no medicine stocks in any of the hospitals in Gaza," Mr Al-Qudra added, calling on the international community to expedite the delivery of aid to Gaza.
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu told US President Joe Biden on Wednesday more than 1,400 Israelis were killed in the October 7 terrorist attacks by Hamas.
